theorem Topology.interior_subset_interior_closure_union_right
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A B : Set X} :
    interior B ⊆ interior (closure (A ∪ B)) := by
  intro x hx
  -- First, upgrade `x ∈ interior B` to `x ∈ interior (closure B)`.
  have hx_closureB : x ∈ interior (closure B) := by
    -- `interior B` is contained in `closure B`.
    have hsub : (interior B : Set X) ⊆ closure B := subset_closure
    -- Apply the monotonicity of `interior`.
    exact (interior_mono hsub) hx
  -- Next, show that `interior (closure B)` is contained in
  -- `interior (closure (A ∪ B))`.
  have hsubset : interior (closure B) ⊆ interior (closure (A ∪ B)) := by
    apply interior_mono
    -- `closure B` is contained in `closure (A ∪ B)` since `B ⊆ A ∪ B`.
    have : closure B ⊆ closure (A ∪ B) := by
      apply closure_mono
      exact Set.subset_union_right
    exact this
  -- Combine the two facts to reach the goal.
  exact hsubset hx_closureB

theorem Topology.closure_inter_closure_subset
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A B : Set X} :
    closure (A ∩ closure B) ⊆ closure A ∩ closure B := by
  intro x hx
  -- `A ∩ closure B` is contained in `A`, hence its closure is contained in `closure A`.
  have hA : (A ∩ closure B : Set X) ⊆ A := by
    intro y hy; exact hy.1
  have hxA : x ∈ closure A := (closure_mono hA) hx
  -- `A ∩ closure B` is also contained in `closure B`, so its closure is contained there too.
  have hB : (A ∩ closure B : Set X) ⊆ closure B := by
    intro y hy; exact hy.2
  have hxB : x ∈ closure B := (closure_mono hB) hx
  exact And.intro hxA hxB

theorem Topology.P3_of_P1_and_P2
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A : Set X} :
    Topology.P1 A → Topology.P2 A → Topology.P3 A := by
  intro hP1 hP2
  -- From `P2` we obtain both `P1` and `P3`; extract the latter.
  exact ((Topology.P2_iff_P1_and_P3 (A := A)).1 hP2).2
